            <div class="col-md-6 animated wow fadeInRight">
                <div class="features_list">
                    <h1 class="text-uppercase">Background</h1>
                    <p>
                        Firstly, it is a fact that Bulgaria is the poorest country in Europe. Secondly, Vidin the capital of the north-west region of Bulgaria is by far the poorest region in Bulgaria.
                        At its peak Vidin had a population of over 62,000 people. A census in 2009 highlighted that the population had dropped to just under 50,000. Like many towns in Bulgaria, Vidin’s decline is characterised by migration, particularly the young, moving to more prosperous parts of Bulgaria and Europe. Despite the fact that roads are crumbling, pavements are dangerous to walk on, many buildings and factories are disused and too many families struggle to manage from day to day this region has the potential to raise itself from the ashes.
                        The mighty Danube flows alongside the town, the landscape including the nearby mountains can be beautiful to the eye, the wildlife is abundant and the people are so friendly.
                        Another huge plus for this region is the Vidin / Calafat (Romania) bridge which is due to open to traffic in 2013 creates new opportunities as will the proposed high speed rail network from Vidin to Sofia. The future can be bright, but only with the right vision and commitment.
                        Villages in the region have different issues to deal with. All villages in the region are declining, the young are moving to the big cities or out of the country altogether thereby leaving an aging population. Unemployment in all villages is high, particularly for those who are from the Roma community. As a result, the economy of these villages is miniscule with little investment from the government.
                        In the UK, education is free up to the age of 19 years. Further education colleges are well resourced and offer a wide variety of vocational programmes. Schools and colleges offer a wide range of qualifications which lead to either university or the world of work. To compare what is available in the UK against what is available here in Bulgaria is like comparing chalk and cheese. In Bulgaria there is a significant lack of opportunities during and after 16 years of age. There is not a day that goes by when I don’t reflect upon how lucky I am to have been born in a country where education and work opportunities existed and exist today. It is embarrassing and sad to think that here we are in 2012 and these same opportunities do not exist in a country which is a member of the European Union.
                        The Vidin region like all regions in Bulgaria has a number of children’s homes. It is very possible that youngsters can be in care from one day old to eighteen years of age and even older. At the time of writing, the children’s home in Novo Selo has 59 residents. For some of these children their ‘home’ has always been a care home of some sort. Unfortunately, for the vast majority of children who grow up in a home there is little future to look forward to after 18 years of age, apart from prostitution and begging. It doesn’t take any imagination to realise that standing on a highway or in a lay-by in the middle of winter trying to generate business or asking people for money with a tin is no fun. This bleak future is due to a number of factors: lack of money to pay for tuition and transport is certainly one, lack of aspiration and motivation to learn is another as is the lack of encouragement and facilities.
                        Working towards a better future
